04426nam a22006975i 9780812209259DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)961585966  a97808122092597 a10.9783/97808122092592doi  a(DE-B1597)449809  a(OCoLC)922638012  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a306.09732231 aBen-Atar, Doron S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaming Lust :bCrimes Against Nature in the Early Republic /cRichard D. Brown, Doron S. Ben-Atar. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b21 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Crimes Against Nature -- tChapter 1. The Sisyphean Battle Against Bestiality -- tChapter 2. The Unlikely Prosecutions of John Farrell and Gideon Washburn -- tChapter 3. Sexual Crisis in the Age of Revolution -- tChapter 4. Fearful Rulers in Anxious Times -- tChapter 5. Puritan Twilight in the New England Republics -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1796, as revolutionary fervor waned and the Age of Reason took hold, an eighty-five-year-old Massachusetts doctor was convicted of bestiality and sentenced to hang. Three years later and seventy miles away, an eighty-three-year-old Connecticut farmer was convicted of the same crime and sentenced to the same punishment. Prior to these criminal trials, neither Massachusetts nor Connecticut had executed anyone for bestiality in over a century. Though there are no overt connections between the two episodes, the similarities of their particulars are strange and striking. Historians Doron S. Ben-Atar and Richard D. Brown delve into the specifics to determine what larger social, political, or religious forces could have compelled New England courts to condemn two octogenarians for sexual misbehavior typically associated with much younger men.The stories of John Farrell and Gideon Washburn are less about the two old men than New England officials who, riding the rough waves of modernity, returned to the severity of their ancestors. The political upheaval of the Revolution and the new republic created new kinds of cultural experience—both exciting and frightening—at a moment when New England farmers and village elites were contesting long-standing assumptions about divine creation and the social order. Ben-Atar and Brown offer a rare and vivid perspective on anxieties about sexual and social deviance in the early republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.1 aBrown, Richard D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220925940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209259.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK